Predicting Need for Phototherapy in the Neonatal ICU

Jack McDonnell

2018-05-07

skim_with(numeric = list(hist = NULL),

1 Background

Babies commonly develop jaundice, the colloquial term for a condition due to elevated levels of bilirubin in the blood (hyperbilirubinemia). For many babies, hyperbilirubinemia is a issue that requires serial monitoring rather than treatment. In more severe cases, however, the bilirubin levels need treatment to come down. The mainstay of treatment is a therapy called phototherapy, which works by isomerizing the bilirubin to a form that can be excreted through the skin. In the rarest of cases, phototherapy fails and the the patient requires an exchange transfusion to avoid the serious consequences of bilirubin encephalopathy.

In the pediatric literature, several factors have have been linked to increased risk of hyperbilirubinemia. These include prematurity, hemolytic disease of the newborn, G6PD deficiency, asphyxia, lethargy, temperature instability, sepsis, acidosis, hypoalbuminemia, and Asian race. Absent from this of known contributing factors is birth weight. Holding other known contributors constant, does birth weight affect the development of clinical jaundice severe enough to require phototherapy?

2 Research Questions

My primary research question is simple: can birth weight be used to predict need for phototherapy in the NICU, adjusting for other relevant covariates? From this simple question I hope to fit 3 clinically useful models:

  1. m0 - a model predicting need for phototherapy based on information readily available to the clinician in the first few hours of an infants life (delivery room model)

  2. m1 - a model predicting need for phototherapy based on information readily available to the clinician in the first few days of an infants life, but prior to onset of clinical jaundice

  3. m2 - a model predicting need for phototherapy once a baby in the NICU is diagnosed with jaundice

My project is relevant because it arms clinicians with a useful framework to predict need for phototherapy for babies at various clinical stages, based on the information typically available at that particular stage.

3 My Data

These data are from the MIMIC-III database (https://mimic.physionet.org). MIMIC contains data from the ICUs (both adult and neonatal) at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center from 2001-2012. It is a freely accessible critical care database useful for performing these kinds of analyses.

The advantage to these data is their fairly large n (7,875 infants), completeness, and level of clinical detail (down to the granular level of cardiac monitor waveforms and pulse rates throughout admission.) A disadvantage is that the data are scattered across multiple .csv files, several of which are prohibitively huge (>30 gig) and thus could not even be opened on any available computer. Due to this, I confined my analysis to the easily obtained and non-computationally intensive ICD-9 codes for the relevant diagnoses and procedures. To get the data into this form took a lot of wrangling and maneuvering - work I mostly accomplished in Stata 15 (see attached do file for the code used.)

3.2 Tidying, Data Cleaning and Data Management

With this first section of code, I create a variable for Asian heritage, which is known to be a risk factor for jaundice. Although it is usually not beneficial to collapse more diverse data into binary categories, here it only matters clinically if an infant is Asian or not (as no other ethnic background has been linked to problems with jaundice).

With this section of code, I generate a factor variable for birth weight categories.

# generate birth weight categories
photo_babies_tidy <- photo_babies_tidy %>% 
    mutate(birth_weight_fac = as.factor(birth_weight_fac)) 
photo_babies_tidy <- photo_babies_tidy %>% 
                mutate(birth_weight_fac = fct_recode(birth_weight_fac,
                                "Extremely Low Birth Weight (ELBW)" = "ELBW",
                                "Very Low Birth Weight (VLBW)" = "VLBW",
                                "Low Birth Weight (LBW)" = "LBW",
                                "Normal Birth Weight" = "0"))
photo_babies_tidy$birth_weight_fac <- fct_relevel(photo_babies_tidy$birth_weight_fac, "Normal Birth Weight", "Low Birth Weight (LBW)", "Very Low Birth Weight (VLBW)", "Extremely Low Birth Weight (ELBW)")

Below I create a factor variable for degree of prematurity. Preterm infants are known to be at increased risk for jaundice.

This now-tidied data set contains data on 7246 subjects. Of these, 2378 were treated with phototherapy. The main predictor in the model is going to be birth_weight_fac, correcting for a number of important factors.

As can be seen above, I converted a number of variables to factors. Most of them end up being 1/0 indicator variables, but a few (like those corresponding to gestational age and birth weight) have several levels.

A number of variables had a priori plausibility as being important to whether or not an infant receives phototherapy, but had negligible or 0 counts in particular data set. An example is G6PD, corresponding to whether an infant had G6PD (glucose-6-phosphate-dehydrogenase) deficiency. I dropped these variables because they could not meaningfully contribute to my analysis.

3.3 Missingness

The only variable with missing data is the factor variable gestational_age_fac - it is missing a substantial number of observations (4467). I will drop these here, since I cannot be sure which category of gestational age these babies would be assigned (and gestational age is a variable of major importance for my research questions).

5 Some Motivating Graphics

ggplot(data = photo_babies_complete, aes(x = jaundice, fill = birth_weight_fac)) + 
    geom_bar() + 
    labs(x = "Received Phototherapy",
         y = "Number of patients",
         title = "Lower Birth Weight Infants Need Phototherapy More Often") + 
  scale_fill_discrete(name = "Birth Weight")

This plot shows the relationship between need for phototherapy and birth weight, and is the primary motivating image for my analysis. There definitely seems to be increased need for phototherapy for babies who are lower in terms of birth weight, but this could be merely due to the association of birth weight with some other factor, like prematurity.

Indeed, one can see below that birth weight is strongly associated with prematurity. This relationship makes intuitive sense, but is especially striking when seen graphically.

ggplot(data = photo_babies_complete, aes(x = gestational_age_fac, fill = birth_weight_fac)) + 
    geom_bar() + 
    labs(x = "Gestational Age",
         y = "Number of patients",
         title = "Premature Babies Weight Less") + 
  scale_fill_discrete(name = "Birth Weight")

So when considering how birth weight plays into ultimate need for phototherapy, I will definitely need to adjust for prematurity as well due to the strength of this relationship.

6 Analysis of m0

6.1 m0 : a model predicting need for phototherapy based on factors knowable immediately after delivery

dd <- datadist(photo_babies_complete)
options(datadist="dd")

m0 <- lrm(phototherapy ~ birth_weight_fac + gestational_age_fac + ethnicity_fac, data = photo_babies_complete, x=TRUE, y=TRUE)

The first model I fit is one predicting need for phototherapy based on factors that are typically known around the time of delivery - gestational age, ethnicity of infant, and birth weight of infant. Our model here has a C-statistic of 0.80 and R2 0.34.

One note- prior to fitting this model, I considered an interaction between gestational_age_fac and birth_weight_fac on the basis of a Spearman plot. However, these variables have multiple levels, including some with very few or empty counts (such as a baby born at 24 weeks with normal birth weight, which makes no sense) so I ultimately did not end up going in this direction.

Based on these residual plots, there are a few higher leverage points but no particularly influential points to contend with. Overall, I am not concerned for the model based on what I see here.

With this model, our C statistic climbs through the roof to 0.94, and the R2 jumps to 0.75. Although it is satisfying to see such high model performance, I am a bit skeptical about these results. The models increase in performance is due to the introduction of this new term for diagnosis of jaundice. Could this increase be merely due to an idiosyncrasy in how the NICU at Beth Israel operates? Specifically, do clinicians there normally not bother coding for jaundice until a babys jaundice levels reach the threshold for phototherapy?

8.2 brief stop: evaluating the relationship between ICD9 coding for jaundice and need for phototherapy in this data set

To answer this question, lets look briefly at m3. I fit this model simply to evaluate the relationship between ICD9 code for jaundice and phototherapy in this particular data set; it turns out that the relationship is strong with a C statistic of 0.87 and R2 of 0.67. So, it must be true that either 1) babies who start to get jaundice in the NICU nearly all progress to treatment levels eventually, or 2) clinicians in this data set coded jaundice largely when the baby was close to treatment levels, or 3) some combination of both.

m3<- lrm(phototherapy ~ jaundice, data = photo_babies_complete)

My analysis is not sensitive enough to determine a sure answer to this question, since I dont have data on the exact timing of the ICD9 codes relative to each other. Given this limitation, the gain in model performance should probably be interpreted with some sobriety. In any case, it may be useful to compare the C statistic obtained when considering just diagnosis of phototherapy in m4 (0.87) to the one obtained in the full model m3 (0.94) - this increase of 7 points in model discrimination was due to the inclusion of all the other covariates and seems clinically meaningful.

With this context in mind, lets turn back to analyzing m2.

9 Model Summaries

Model Description R2 C statistic
m0 based on information available in the delivery room 0.34 0.80
m1 based on information available in first 24 hours 0.36 0.81
m2 model incorporating diagnosis of jaundice 0.75 0.94

In this table, model discrimination increases as we go from less clinical information about a patient (earlier in the hospital course) to more. A major factor in predicting need for phototherapy is simply being diagnosed with jaundice by a clinician.

10 Conclusions

  1. Can birth weight be used to predict need for phototherapy in the NICU, adjusting for other relevant covariates?

    • Yes. Birth weight is useful in predicting needing for phototherapy at various stages of a patients stay.

    • Indeed, birth weight was a significant predictor in every model I fit.

    • A logical next step is to gain more insight into the missing data on gestational age that I dropped.

  2. How is this study relevant?

    • This study provides NICU clinicians with a framework for predicting need for phototherapy at various stages of their patients admissions

    • From a research perspective, it is an early but important formative step toward the creation of a clinical prediction tool usable in NICUs across the country.

  3. Reflections on the process.

    • This project was overall the easiest for me to perform (in comparison to previous projects) because I had clear goals from the start, and I didnt feel hindered by strict requirements for its completion. I really enjoyed the more open-ended nature of this analysis.

    • The hardest part for me coding-wise was in bringing together disparate .csv files and mining them for ICD9 codes. I tried to do this in R, got nowhere, and ultimately resorted to using Stata. In the future, I would like to be able to do everything in R.

    • I struggled with understanding what to do about the missing data for gestational age, particularly when a simple imputation I performed lumped the thousands of missing gestational age babies into the 25 week category (all with normal birth weights to boot.) I experimented with multiple imputation for a while but ultimately consulted Dr.Love, who recommended dropping them completely for this analysis. For future projects with these data, Im going to find a better solution.

    • Like all projects, and the course in general, I learned a great deal (even if this cognitive expansion was sometimes a bit painful!).
